Most of the data is inherently imbalanced due to the typical characteristics of animals that end up in shelters. We address the class imbalance within the outcome_type target variable by incorporating SMOTE directly into our cross-validation training process. For these imbalances within the explanatory features, we leverage the inherent robustness of the XGBoost algorithm. Tree-based ensemble methods like XGBoost are generally less sensitive to skewed or imbalanced distributions in predictor variables compared to some other machine learning algorithms.

Methods & Results

Parallel-processing setup

cores <- parallel::detectCores() - 1
registerDoParallel(cores = cores)

Train / test split and CV folds

set.seed(2025)
split  <- initial_split(df, strata = outcome_type, prop = 0.80)
train  <- training(split)
test   <- testing(split)
folds  <- vfold_cv(train, v = 10, strata = outcome_type)


rec <- recipe(outcome_type ~ ., data = train) %>%
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(), threshold = 0.01) %>%  
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors())            %>%         
  step_zv(all_predictors())                       %>%          
  step_smote(outcome_type)                        %>%          # SMOTE balancing
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())                      

rec_prep <- prep(rec, training = train)
n_preds  <- ncol(juice(rec_prep, all_predictors()))

XGBoost spec

xgb_spec <- boost_tree(
  trees          = tune(),
  mtry           = tune(),
  tree_depth     = tune(),
  learn_rate     = tune(),
  min_n          = tune(),
  loss_reduction = tune(),
  sample_size    = tune(),
  stop_iter      = 20
) %>%
  set_engine(
    "xgboost",
    objective   = "binary:logistic",
    eval_metric = "auc",
    nthread     = cores
  ) %>%
  set_mode("classification")

Hyper-parameter space

param_set <- parameters(
  trees(range = c(200L, 1500L)),
  mtry(range  = c(1L, n_preds)),
  tree_depth(),
  learn_rate(),
  min_n(),
  loss_reduction(),
  sample_size = sample_prop()
)

Workflow

wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(rec) %>%
  add_model(xgb_spec)

metric_fun <- metric_set(roc_auc, pr_auc, accuracy, sens, yardstick::spec, f_meas)
options(tidymodels.progress = TRUE)

Racing-ANOVA tuning

set.seed(2025)
xgb_race <- tune_race_anova(
  wf,
  resamples = folds,
  param_set = param_set,
  metrics   = metric_fun,
  control   = control_race(
    verbose_elim  = TRUE,
    parallel_over = "everything",
    save_pred     = TRUE
  )
)

Finalise & evaluate on hold-out test

best_params <- select_best(xgb_race, metric = "roc_auc")
final_wf    <- finalize_workflow(wf, best_params)

final_res <- last_fit(final_wf, split, metrics = metric_fun)

ROC-AUC

preds <- collect_predictions(final_res)
preds$y_true <-ifelse(preds$outcome_type=="Adopted",1,0)

roc_obj <- roc(preds$y_true, preds$.pred_Adopted)
auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
print(paste("AUC:", round(auc_value, 3)))
## [1] "AUC: 0.822"
roc_df <- data.frame(
  tpr = roc_obj$sensitivities,
  fpr = 1 - roc_obj$specificities
)

ggplot(roc_df, aes(x = fpr, y = tpr)) +
  geom_line(color = "#2196f3", size = 1.2) +
  geom_abline(linetype = "dashed", color = "grey50") +
  annotate("text", x = 0.7, y = 0.2, 
           label = paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3)), size = 5, color = "#2196f3") +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve: Adopted vs Not Adopted",
       x = "False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)",
       y = "True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 15)

df %>%
  count(color_group, health_status, name = "n") %>%  
  group_by(color_group) %>%                             
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) %>%                          
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = color_group, y = prop,
             fill = health_status)) +
  geom_col(width = .7) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format(accuracy = 1)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
  labs(title = "Health-status share by coat colour",
       x = "Coat colour", y = "Share of animals") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank())

Observation :

Puppies/kittens, juveniles, adults, and seniors appear in almost the same proportions across every coat colour, confirming age distribution doesnt vary by coat colour.
